n: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pierre","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From New Testament Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Pierre II de Rostrenen was born about 1137, in Rostrenen, Côtes-du-Nord, Brittany, France, his father, Pierre I de Rostrenen, was 42 and his mother, Mrs. Pierre I de Rostenen, was 29. He married Mahete de Fougères. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1137–":"umbes 1137–Surnud","1137–Male":"1137–Surnud","1167–1241":"1167–1241","1169–Female":"1169–Surnud","1171–Female":"1171–Surnud","1175–1214":"1175–1214","1137–Female":"1137–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1097–Male":"1097–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1190":"1190","en